A Cracker in the Pines Pay was board and thirty dollars, a salty horse between our legs, a plug each day of tobacco and two hot meals of hog and eggs. We rode hard all the daylight hours among the pine stands hunting scrubs, then back to camp at each nightfall to quell our hunger with some grub. We were rugged like the saw-grass that chokes the sunlight from the glade, yet gentle as the Spanish Moss whose tatted veil airily swayed. They called us Florida Crackers and I suppose the name was fair; our cow whips would crack like thunder as their rawhide spit through the air. We crossed hammocks and deep gulleys to push the beeves toward our pen, then once we reached the crevice we rode back out to do it again. We would work the herd for branding, cut the calves from their mama's sides, and when the irons heated we'd burn our mark upon their hides. Now-a-days the cow hunts are over and the barbed wire has been strung. Old cowboy types have faded to gray; worn out knees no longer young. Pure blooded cattle feed on baled hay, the markets now reached by truck, so as the sun descends at night, this Cracker has run out of luck. Like the scrub cows of yesterday you can find me back in the pines. I never did grow accustomed to the bunkhouse's close confines. My pony stands gaunt but shows no sign of wanting to call it quits, so we wander freely through scant days awaiting our own obits.

The Dark, Blue Sea ‚Äî Lord Byron There is a pleasure in the pathless woods, There is a rapture on the lonely shore, There is society where none intrudes, By the deep sea, and music in its roar: I love not man the less, but nature more, From these our interviews, in which I steal From all I may be, or have been before, To mingle with the universe, and feel What I can ne'er express, yet cannot all conceal.- Roll on, thou deep and dark blue ocean-roll! Ten thousand fleets sweep over thee in vain; Man marks the earth with ruin-his control Stops with the shore;-upon the watery plain The wrecks are all thy deed, nor doth remain A shadow of man's ravage, save his own, When for a moment, like a drop of rain, He sinks into thy depths with bubbling groan, Without a grave, unknell'd, uncoffin'd, and unknown. His steps are not upon thy paths-thy fields Are not a spoil for him-thou dost arise And shake him from thee; the vile strength he wields For earth's destruction thou dost all despise, Spurning him from thy bosom to the skies, And send'st him, shivering in thy playful spray, And howling, to his gods, where haply lies His petty hope in some near port or bay, And dashest him again to earth: there let him lay. The armaments which thunderstrike the walls Of rock-built cities, bidding nations quake, And monarchs tremble in their capitals, The oak leviathans, whose huge ribs make Their clay creator the vain title take Of lord of thee, and arbiter of war; These are thy toys, and, as the snowy flake, They melt into thy yeast of waves, which mar Alike the armada's pride, or spoils of Trafalgar. Thy shores are empires, changed in all save thee- Assyria, Greece, Rome, Carthage, what are they? Thy waters washed them power while they were free, And many a tyrant since: their shores obey The stranger, slave or savage; their decay Has dried up realms to deserts:-not so thou, Unchangeable, save to thy wild waves' play- Time writes no wrinkle on thine azure brow- Such as creation's dawn beheld, thou rollest now. Thou glorious mirror, where the Almighty's form Glasses itself in tempests; in all time Calm or convulsed-in breeze, or gale, or storm, Icing the pole, or in the torrid clime Dark-heaving; boundless, endless and sublime- The image of eternity-the throne Of the invisible; even from out thy slime The monsters of the deep are made; each zone Obeys thee; thou goest forth, dread, fathomless, alone. And I have loved thee, ocean! And my joy Of youthful sports was on thy breast to be Borne, like thy bubbles, onward: from a boy I wanton'd with thy breakers-they to me Were a delight; and if the freshening sea Made them a terror-'twas a pleasing fear, For I was as it were a child of thee, And trusted to thy billows far and near, And laid my hand upon thy mane - as I do here.

From when the great khan, avatar of the destroyer, sacked the city. From the edge of the light I see caravans traveling. I feel better we aren't alone. Even if the camel riders hymns chill me to my bone. ... We‚Äôve reached the city, An island fortress, connected by a long stone bridge. The huge port bustles with ships and sailors, The scent of fish and salt heavy in the air. In the crowded bazaar, dregs of every race and people barter and shout, Their voices rising above the clamor of carts and camel bells. Jason says this is where we‚Äôll find passage‚Äî But something about this place feels dangerous, A Viper lurking beneath the crowd. ... We found a cheap tavern to rest. Jason returned from his wanderings with an icon, A saint from his faith, one known for standing against the crowd. I walked the streets alone, The air thick with the scent of incense and the cries of merchants. We plan to meet the prince soon, But first, we must learn what powers rules this place. ... A woman approached me at dusk, Her eyes like emeralds, her skin pale as snow, A strange beauty that left me breathless. She whispered of needing help, And without thinking, I followed her into the shadowed alley. But I was ambushed, Three men, their faces like that of pugs, lunged at me. The fight was quick and brutal‚Äî My blade found its mark, And soon they lay still, Blood pooling in the dust. The woman fell to her knees, Crying out for mercy, Her voice trembling as she spoke: "Your beloved is at the prince‚Äôs palace." How she knew this, I cannot say. Perhaps it was a lie, A trick to lure me further into this web of deceit. I let her go, Her emerald eyes haunting me as she fled. A mistake, perhaps‚Äî But the promise of my beloved calls me forward. I‚Äôll tell Jason and Will in the morning, No need to disturb them now. ... We arrived at the prince's palace. The walls of the fortress towered over us, The guards stood still, covered head to toe in golden armor, Each piece of their scale-like plating glinting in the light, Resembling the scales of a dragon. Their cloaks were a pure white, As pristine as the flag that flew above the palace‚Äî A black lion, drawn in sharp calligraphy of their tongue, Majestic and menacing. Inside the hall, the air was thick with judgment. The prince sat high on his throne, His eyes dark as he watched his brothers kneel before him. They were sentenced to die‚Äî Strangled for the crime of "false witness to a false prophet." Their faces were pale, but they did not beg. The weight of the prince‚Äôs word was final. "This city is about to be set alight," Will whispered to me, his voice barely audible over the heavy silence. His words sent a chill down my spine. I could see it too‚Äî The tension in the air, like a storm gathering on the horizon. If my beloved lay within these walls, I must tread carefully. The prince‚Äôs justice was swift, The flames of this brewing conflict may consume us all...

Notes from the East: Part one. My brothers in arms are seeking the entrance. We bear the garb of long fallen heroes. So their spirit may lead us to where they could not go. This is the beginning of the journey, I am excited for our sanctification. ... We passed the river, where the sons of Rurik were enslaved. A people conquered by pulpit prostitutes, Made in the broken image of the eternal city. But the people remain. Conquered, perverted, left to rot. I pray the army within the hidden city of the East can save these lot. ... I write at night, I cannot sleep. I hear the whispers of the dead, Beneath this great rune. I hear this was the sight of our ancestral God's Before they came west, before the Slaves instilled their rot. We must continue on - despite our fears. I must find the city, where my beloved lies. My brothers sleep now, I'll keep watch. The horrors we'll see before the end shake me to my core. ... We've moved past the lands of the Arya, These dry lands are inhabited by the barbaric tribes. They remember the Twilight of the God's, They remember their Demise. We've found a withered guide, He's different - a man with Blue eyes. He claims to know the path, To the city within the earth. My brothers don't trust him but what's our luck. We'll continue on with the guide, All he talks about is his fallen dog. ... I had a dream last night, Of my beloved, Her voice lost in the city, singing. A song only I can hear. The others cannot catch its melody‚Äî The guide says it‚Äôs my own. We all have a song, he says, But the price of following it may be damnation. He calls me a troubadour, Unlike my brothers in soldiers‚Äô attire. I did not choose these clothes‚Äî They were chosen for me. But why, I do not know. As I stare into the fire, Her silhouette flickers in the flames, Dancing, beckoning. I must sleep soon. I mustn‚Äôt let the madness smother the dream. ... Traveling among the mountains, Going into the graveyard of many empires. We find ascetics, in a circle with their master. They are listening to the silence of each other, I won't intrude, I don't know their powers. ... So many statues, torn down in iconoclastic fervor. My brother in late Hellenic armor smiles at this. I question him on our cultures destruction. He states it's all "pagan idolatry" and "degenerate". I stayed silent, disturbed by this statement. I don't understand my brother, why is he on this journey. This journey to destroy all values to arise new ones. He holds on to the past whilst wanting to bring it's destruction. Nevertheless he is my brother. I'll keep this in mind. ... Fire and blood! Our camp was attacked, The guide slain, his breath fading beneath the stars. Before he slipped away, he whispered to me, ‚ÄúContinue on. Remember the city. It is yours now.‚Äù I hold his words close, But they weigh heavy, as though I carry not a map, But the very stones of the city itself. We drove back the assailants, Clay-made creatures, their eyes hollow, Their skin breaking apart beneath our blades. They crumble as the statues before them, But something darker lies behind their creation. I wonder what hands molded them, And what greater evils wait ahead.

url_description: Get ready to experience the Echoes of Wars, as Viking Hirdman, in your headphones. ___________________________________________ This gorgerous version was done by The Pagan Minstrel and can be listened to it here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=M6Us4l11bLE ___________________________________________ If you enjoyed this video and my content, please consider supporting me on Kofi! - https://ko-fi.com/potan Or become my Youtube Channel member! - https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCS_e1KVkuo8y1mLwEVI3i9g/join ___________________________________________ The Battle of Stamford Bridge took place on September 25, 1066, in Yorkshire, England, and was a pivotal moment in English history. King Harold Godwinson of England faced off against an invading Norwegian force led by King Harald Hardrada and Harold's own brother, Tostig Godwinson, who had allied with Hardrada. The Norwegian forces, having just secured a victory at the Battle of Fulford a few days earlier, were caught by surprise when Harold Godwinson‚Äôs army arrived at Stamford Bridge after a rapid march from southern England. Despite being unprepared and without their armor (which had been left behind on their ships), the Norwegians fought fiercely. The battle was hard-fought, with the English eventually breaking through the Norwegian lines. A legendary account describes a lone Viking warrior holding off the English troops at the bridge before being overcome. King Harald Hardrada was killed by an arrow to the throat, and Tostig also fell in battle. The English victory effectively ended the Viking threat to England. However, this triumph was short-lived. Just three days later, Harold Godwinson received news that William of Normandy had landed on the southern coast, leading to the Battle of Hastings just weeks later. The Battle of Stamford Bridge marked the end of the Viking Age in England and set the stage for the Norman Conquest.

The Anglo-Hellenic Colony of New Smyrna When a Scottish physician, Andrew Turnbell, wanted to aid in British production of several resources within the newly acquired Florida territory, he looked towards the Mediterranean people. Due to the British having the Balearic island of Menorca, which at the time held a large Greek population (due to fleeing the Ottoman occupation), he had traveled there for business, including to the Greek-Anatolian city of Smyrna. It was there that he both had met his wife, Maria Gracia Dura Bin, and where he hatched the idea to colonize Florida with Mediterraneans. In the spring of 1768, Turnbell launched his colonization mission with 1,403 men, many of whom were Greek. After arriving in St.Augustine, Florida, he headed southbound, and set up his colonial mission in Mosquito Bay. He would name his new colony after the city that his wife was born in, as well as the name for his new Greek colony: New Smyrna. Many of the colonizers would be promised land for work. Right away, the colony started producing high amounts of Indigo, Hemp, and Cotton. For the first 5 years, the colony was becoming wealthy, and was becoming well established, as well as receiving high amounts of support from Britain. Unfortunately, just as with Jamestown just 150 years prior, indians would prove to be harmful and murderous through countless raids. Due to droughts and eventual mistreatment by the overseer, during the height of the American Revolution, Governor Tonyn of East Florida had made a promise to all the residents of New Smyrna that if they joined his Loyalist Militia, they would receive land and protection (against Turnbell). Nearly the entire colony had joined Tonyn's Militia, and ended up residing in St.Augustine, thus leaving New Smyrna to die. Some, however, still stayed and worked, continuing to produce for the British Empire until it was ceded to the Spanish. To this day, New Smyrna Beach, Florida, is a a thriving city that is 85% White.

His art was full of symbolism and in fact was a direct influence on the popular psychedelic style of graphic design of the late 1960s. Fidus was a deeply spiritual man. Aphorism 134. TO WHAT EXTENT WE MUST BEWARE OF PITY. Pity, in so far as it actually gives rise to suffering‚Äîand this must be our only point of view here‚Äîis a weakness, like every other indulgence in an injurious emotion. It increases suffering throughout the world, and although here and there a certain amount of suffering may be indirectly diminished or removed altogether as a consequence of pity, we must not bring forward these occasional consequences, which are on the whole insignificant, to justify the nature of pity which, as has already been stated, is prejudicial. Supposing that it prevailed, even if only for one day, it would bring humanity to utter ruin. In itself the nature of pity is no better than that of any other craving; it is only where it is called for and praised‚Äîand this happens when people do not understand what is injurious in it, but find in it a sort of joy‚Äîthat a good conscience becomes attached to it; it is only then that we willingly yield to it, and do not shrink from acknowledging it. In other circumstances where it is understood to be dangerous, it is looked upon as a weakness; or, as in the case of the Greeks, as an unhealthy periodical emotion the danger of which might be removed by temporary and voluntary discharges. If a man were to undertake the experiment of deliberately devoting his attention to the opportunities afforded by practical life for the exercise of pity, and were over and over again to picture in his own mind the misery he might meet with in his immediate surroundings, he would inevitably become melancholy and ill. If, however, he wished in any sense of the word to serve humanity as a physician, he would have to take many precautions with respect to this feeling, as otherwise it would paralyse him at all critical moments, undermine the foundations of his knowledge, and unnerve his helpful and delicate hand. Nietzsche, daybreak

Continue on, northern son, give it your all. Our burning souls can almost feel the upcoming fall. This rotted structure can no longer hold our delirious love. Our path to be a cut above. The weak look at us, hatred in their eyes. They despise what they are and thrash at all in a lie. The meek and lack of will is a poison of this time. Our new state will be free of this, all in due time. Deity in infancy, We his warring infantry. Our ancient souls all in one. The fidelity for him is our ultimate gain. Us peninsular children, Our home is decaying. Embarrassing the light of life. Will finally put an end to our fight.

Folk wandering Gathering around the pyre, Remembering what transpired. Retelling those ancient tales. Great heroes, followers of the hale. A battle in the mire, A forgone conflict, A folk against that city. A city of the paralyzed. To be delivered it's demise The age of the abyss, The elders tell us not to miss. We know not of the rot, But it shall not be forgot. Holy fire, we cried in jubilation. That damned city, it's horrid population! Remember their rot, Keep to the pact. That of blood and its mission. Our Holy Leader, His destroyed kingdom, We who keep his truth, A tide against the storm of misrule. The folk wander, carrying the flame, A saga of justice, etching their name. They will return, in times of reform. Their rage goes, against those who break that law.

The throws of every birth are painful, but it would be criminal to prevent a birth for the sake of the pains, and it would be just as senseless to postpone a birth through whatever means. ‚Äî Kurt Eggers

We know that each day we must reject some knowledge as deception, when in our search we have encountered greater truths. This search is more sacred to us than all the religious writings of the world combined. Nothing can replace personal experience, personal realisation and personal decision. ‚Äî Kurt Eggers, 'The struggle for knowledge'

Solar tide, Affirms my ride. A chorus of laughter. In the wheel of slaughter. Eyes poised, Rusted coins. Long gone altars, To finished ideals. The birth of a new flower, Inherited characteristics, Will this halt or enable its growth? Our new son we cradle in our arms. Will he be sick? Or will he surpass. As we go to the mountain pass, Seeing the centurion's final slumber. We pass over the tiber, In their towers they cower. Thinking it could never happen to them. A resurgence of northern blood. A resurgence of the sun. Our deity is born, his will won't be scorned. The crown of thorns, will be set to the torch. We sit at his throne, Just a babe in our time. Our geist, our folk, he is coming. His host will be mad, No clemency to be had. Our oath is done, The labor must begin.

A quote from Cats and Dogs - By H. P. Lovecraft Beauty, sufficiency, ease, and good manners‚Äîwhat more can civilisation require? We have them all in the divine little monarch who lounges gloriously on his silken cushion before the hearth. Loveliness and joy for their own sake‚Äîpride and harmony and coordination‚Äîspirit, restfulness, and completeness‚Äîall here are present, and need but a sympathetic disillusionment for worship in full measure. What fully civilised soul but would eagerly serve as high-priest of Bast? The star of the cat, I think, is just now in the ascendant, as we emerge little by little from the dreams of ethics and democracy which clouded the nineteenth century and raised the grubbing and unlovely dog to the pinnacle of sentimental regard. Whether a renaissance of monarchy and beauty will restore our Western civilisation, or whether the forces of disintegration are already too powerful for even the fascist sentiment to check, none may yet say; but in the present moment of cynical world-unmasking between the pretence of the eighteen-hundreds and the ominous mystery of the decades ahead we have at least a flash of the old pagan perspective and the old pagan clearness and honesty.

Volunteers - Kurt Eggers If the wealthy are happy And moan with comfort The evening wind brings us A distant yearning. We have no flag We unroll in the storm. We wear no insignia Our command is the growl of thunder Of distant guns. We come together When it gets dark. And when iron strikes iron That is our battle song. We climb up from the factories And come with heavy step From the plough. We unknown soldiers, We nameless army. We hold to lost trenches And claw tight to poor soil, No one knows our deeds Aside from us ourselves. But our mouth has become silent And our lips are hard. We are of a different kind We warriors out of joy. We know no answer to your questions About the why. We know nothing to say And remain silent. But our blood will speak When our eyes close In battle.

Rune'd tongue, Speaks wondrous truths. The ear of the tyrant, Cannot bear its tunes. Golden Lyre, patron of lyricists. We give our thanks to you, Us Bragr, us who try to scribe. The tales of heroes past and present. Oh, we seek the gilded Apple, Our veneration of youth, We drink the mead, To seek the language of divinity.
Always speeding forward Endless toil, My soul recoils If I ever slacken my pace.

cleaned_message: Blast the trumpets of the new age, Our land, free from nostalgia. Liberated from the chains of the past. The sound of our music destroys all paralysis. Our vanguard, a band of brothers. Armed with our faith. Keep stern, keep strong. We must finish our mighty song. Our flower is decrepit, but it still has potential. The rebirth will be instrumental. Our mad race to the end. A maelstrom of youth; a frenzy of ambition. A new founding stock for our state. Us second son's, bereaved of our make. Reaving the old, clerics of combat. Finishing this crisis, acquiring lost meaning.
Daily reminder to tell your mom you love her.

Riding out, Bearing the tidal waves, You must stay hard, in the face of the storm. Guide your ship, Just stay afloat, Remove the excess, Throw away the garbage. This ship will see the shore, This ship will see the horizon. We will not sink, We will continue to go on.

We Germans, by Kurt Eggers Our heartbeat is Like the surf of the sea. Like the roar of the waves Does our blood pulse. Like wind and clouds Are our thoughts, Which cross the expanse of worlds. And our yearning is Like the foaming sea That the storm churns up. Our faith is Like the light of the sun, A warming and glowing That comes from the divinity And goes to it. Where the elements, harnessed, Rule the world There is also a bit of our light We who strive for the whole, We Germans.
No Turning Back A race war song for National Socialists all across the world. White man, fight back!

Reborn This is struggle, This is faith! We don't wait, For our fate! Our blood guides us! Against the false doctrines! Our struggle binds us! In our never ending pact of blood! The clash of spirits is increasing, Our hearts are beating, We will win this holy war, For Europe is our home! The Duty to our Will, It will be fulfilled, to overcome our race. One more yank of the endless chain. The truth will manifest, Our courage is endless, We are manifestations of the Will. By the right of the mad rider; our conquest is assured.

Waiting for the feeling to arrive Army of madness go forth, go forth. Leave this place, leave the out the door. Your inferiors resent your divine sight. We will go, make sure we're out of sight. The armory will give us the edge, These weapons of God's will be our pledge. This rotted world will be avenged! Magic, mystery, and fairies will return. Logi! Your arms! they are so red. They scream and shout as they spit lead. Vrrym spits the serpent, poison so hot. Destroying the chapels of the gilded gods. Tiwas, your hands, they throw so far. Boom, goes the dynamite, fast goes our car. We're faster than death, we'll go so far. Beware, beware, the great maw of Garm. We've gone free of the old world, Full of so much gloom. We're here in the new world, all birthed anew. We give praise to the trees, since we've come forth. In our minds we're here, our bodies must come; after the revolutions through.

I sing: Away with equality! Away with justice! Away with fraternity! Whores they are, O Freedom, Leave them and rise with me! The Winds reply: Long live elegance! Long live originality! Long live exaggeration! I sing: Away with democracy! Away with universal suffrage! Away with the Masses! Whores they are, O liberty, Leave them and rise with me! The Winds reply: Long live disproportion! Long live quality! Long with poetry rare! I sing: Away with politics! Away with parliament! Away with communism! Whores they are, O liberty, Leave them and rise with me! The Winds reply: All glory to difference! Long live distinction! Be atypical! Unique! The strongest! The fastest! The most colorful! An excerpt of 'To every man, a New Task every day!: inequality and the Artocracy' by F.T Marinetti

-German Faith- Kurt Eggers When our questioning Echoes in the wind, When our complaining Becomes nothing before fate, Then our faith gropes To the clouds. When our eyes become tired From suffering and doubt, When on earth Storms roar and houses collapse, Faith is like solid ground in the wild sea. Whoever in the distress of the present Can believe in the beauty of the future, That person is stronger than even the deepest suffering Of his heart. Whoever is strong in faith, is victor in the future, And only the strong reaches the land of the future, The meaning of all seeking and willing is being strong. Whoever believes in his strength, also believes in the strength Of his folk. And from this faith arises the eternal Reich.

Rejuvenation Lighting the way, I move and sway. The dance of creation. Leads to destruction. Blinding faith, Praise the deaf. Without voice. Into the chasm. Incandescent staff, Casts out the chaff. World of wills, Seas of change. Traitors cry with glee, Look upon as they flee. Decrying prophecy. Fearing Reciprocity. Alchemists choir, Mends the spire. Age of iron, Idunns fruit required.
Von Savigny on Volkgeist as foundation of law.

The host draws near Like mad dogs we gather upon the hill, We think with glee what wondrous blood we'll spill. Our mad eyes go from side to side. We are living in the moment, our thoughts fleeing, dancing in our minds. Under our banner of the sun, Over the delirious city. The people are half baked, We inspire their enmity. But they have no action, To defend their prosperity. We march, lit alight, gathered in song. We cry out to the battle we sing along. The victory draws near, our madness claws it's way here. Our king throws his mighty spear.
Awake, drawing breath Walking through the sands of time. Tired but never asleep, I walk towards the edge of greatness.
Life is nothing but the search for the eternal self in love and struggle, in the rhythm of light and darkness, the eternal movement to reconnect with the divine spark.

"If a man have not order within him He can not spread order about him; And if a man have not order within him His family will not act with due order; And if the prince have not order within him He can not put order in his dominions." ‚Äî Pound

Yearnings for far away lands As a child I dreamed of Russia, Not the Russia of the early millennia, Russia in depression and ethnic strife. But of Russia, bold, courageous, and vast. From the misty Baltic to the small port of Vladivostok. The Russia my grandmother taught me. Later, I studied history and was enraptured by the flower of France. The glorious nation that all Europe was centered. From the Nordic normans to the ostentatious occitans. A dream of France, I seek to still see. When I read about the struggles of Germany, Brought low by international finance. My heart sunk still, a nation of poets and artisans. Destroyed by the merchants whim. Until it was saved by him, for a short time. My dreams, still as dreams grow still. I will see the France of my dreams, conquerors of outremer; unifiers of Europe. Russia, reborn from its Slavic essence, no longer tied down by trying to be the Greeks, or the Dutch, or the Mongols. But Russia. Germany, once again made a land of poets and mystery, where its folk are first and its expression limitless. And finally my home, finally will find its expression. Free from the shackles of alien forces.

Cast corruption aside As I follow a guide, he states the laws of life. 'First, you must destroy yourself' 'in the face of Destiny, you are nothing.' 'remake yourself, in the guise of victory' 'without victory in your heart, you will never achieve it.' 'Defend yourself from future degradation' 'become a holy vessel, an avatar of creation.' As we make it to the town, the old guide looks at me from under his wide brim. 'Keep these in mind son, you will always be on the right path.' As I turn back to respond, he is gone. I keep these thoughts, as I enter the town inhabited by the empty.

The protest of the calm world directs itself fundamentally against the creatively restless ‚Äòheretic‚Äô, and this protest dresses itself just as fundamentally with fine sounding, and very often also religiously embellished slogans. ‚Äî Kurt Eggers
Finally finished this drawing. Hopefully painting goes according to plan ‚ù§Ô∏è‚Äçü©π

Maiden, maiden, with three names. I dare to thee, come to play. I have been, enraptured by thy song. I have nowhere yet to belong. Oh you are such a lovable beast, Am I yet to be the feast. You play such elegant games, Have I yet been led astray. Why am I gone, From these lands Every coming torchs To my hand. I am yet to be engulfed. I give myself to your rays, My unflinching love of those dying days. I will be reborn in truth. After it all, so will you. The burn, it's all encompassing. Your will it must be against. I seek forgiveness, my chest bare as my soul. You are my goal.

‚ÄúAll happiness on earth, my friends, Only comes from struggle! Yes, to be a faithful friend, It takes the smoke of battle! Only one in three are friends: Brothers to their final breath, Equals before enemies; Free - in facing death!‚Äù ‚Äî Friedrich Nietzsche

Beauty and ugliness Beauty inherently by its very nature functions as a revolt, against the revulsion of its dialectical opposite, ugliness In the act alone, of the observation of beauty, or its creation, one contributes within the eternal conflict against the procreative tendencies of the self reinforcing unbeautiful. Ugliness exists as a self reinforcing phenomena, ugliness breeds further ugliness at a rate far more severe than the creation of beauty - for when what is beautiful is combined in the precense of what is ugly, the result is that the beautiful appears less so, and the ugliness of the ugly is only amplified by the competitive nature of human observation. Build a concrete high rise next to an ancient cathedral, and the scenery of the cathedral will still be ruined regardless of its initial wonder. Place a parking lot and a rest stop next to even the greatest natural wonders and said wonders will lose a part of the 'soul' - value, that initially made them so inherently beautiful. In man too, the breeding of the dysgenic with the beautiful will lead to the decay of said beauty in favor of the dysgenic genetic elements - there is a built in dynamic to prevent this phenomena, attraction. It is in that phenomena that a core aspect of our "moral righteousness" if one could call it that is revealed. On an universal scale, the jew does no inherent wrong in fighting against the aryan by any means necessary, just as the aryan does no wrong in perpetrating industrial genocide - both merely act within their personal racial nature for self preservation - nature is uncaring about the battles of wolfpacks. But we can look for an objective moral right elsewhere, we can look to beauty - for beauty employs a primarily static constant - it is at its core a physical reflection of the archetypal absolutes, beauty is an extension of instinctive desire. In beauty are both Eros and Thanatos. The desire to live, and that to die. The desire to create life, and the desire to end it. In beauty, can we proclaim ourselves truly superior, it is a primary merit of our struggle.

THE LAST DESIRE By Nietzsche So would I die As then I saw him die, The friend, who like a god Into my darkling youth Threw lightning‚Äôs light and fire: Buoyant yet deep was he, Yea, in the battle‚Äôs strife With the happy dancer‚Äôs heart. Amid the warriors His was the lightest heart, Amid the conquerors His brow was dark with thought ‚Äî He was a fate poised on his destiny: Unbending, casting thought into the past And future, such was he. Fearful beneath the weight of victory, Yet chanting, as both victory and death Came hand and hand to him. Commanding even as he lay in death, And his command that man annihilate. So would I die As then I saw him die, Victorious and destroying.

cleaned_message: Noise and plastic The growling of the car grows as I approach the city. The city, full of disdain and lies. This city, where dreams and hope die. I hate going to the city, but I must go. The malaise is palpable, The people are incalculable. Everyone speaks, nothing is said. I feel the growing madness, it's in my head. These poleis, anathema to beauty. Everything is fake, poisonous to our nature. Fire, FIRE is the method to fix our ailment. To curtail the endless derailment. This neverending disaster, debate to reason. It's absurd. We must burn it all, leave the gates open. So we can be heard.

God why did you leave me, I have you my all, I must fall. Into this deep abyss, I will miss. You my love, my Goddess, forgive. This plastic world, you made alive. You made it so, I could thrive. I did all I could, but forgot I would. Forgive me, my loved one. I will pick up the pieces, Put together into one. I'll be better for you, In the next cycle, once again.

The great temptation Every once in awhile, I think to myself 'I'm so tired' Wouldn't it be easier to return to the herd? Where I would be comfortable but never heard. I could go day and night, Free from cosmic stress and fright. No duty but individual pleasure, Endless consumption without measure. It would be easy, yes it would, I could live like I never would. I could be free, I could be safe. But I would never forgive myself, I know what's right.

There is but one reality, that reality is the whole. As a part of the whole we have a duty to overcome ourselves, for the prosperity of our folk. I am of the whole, I am of the Creator; the self created. Recognizing the interconnectedness of the divine, and its many paths of manifestation. My purpose, is the creators purpose. My Path is the path of the creator's self realization. My Path is the path of divine consciousness. This great recognition of our evolutionary duty, towards higher being unto that of deity. My destiny, as a race is Godhood.

The lich King From the east, comes the beast. A king, who is said to have conquered death. A king that seeks dominion over our land. Its shadow grows every closer. They burn the holy women, They throw the icons into the fire. A darkening horde of the slave. The darkening horde grows ever closer At our gates, they claim to save our race. 'Bow down to our king, he is a loving God.' But they sacrifice women and children for false belief. Is this a loving God? We go into hiding, keeping the fire of faith. The noblest and the brave, that is the divine. We return in earnest, the undead God is fat. And his followers have lost faith.

Stay firm, stay firm, Oh son of the West. Stay firm, stay alert, You are on a quest. The gods of the past are dead, The gods of the present of dying. We must seek the new, We must seek his freeing. Man, that glorious animal, between divine and rational. A warring personality, a delusional soul. We must find the key, To free ourselves at home. He will be reborn, The horn must be blown. For the end of the days, To secure the age.

Spirit of flowers Love It's the conquest of death When you're in love, you'll always be remembered. In the act, you become one soul. The birth of a new soul brings about clarity. A new mission, a new goal. We seek the next step in our ancestral quest. Towards that ancient light in our blood. War and combat, it's the greatest act of love. If it is done right, the love of the spirit of the mother; Guides you to strike down the other. For Florida I bring myself high, for when I am low she keeps me. The creation of a Temple in your name, Formation of a cult in your likeness. Mother Florida, we'll make a culture as your avatar. Mother Florida, you are my love.

The great labor In all things the Will resides, Reaching, grappling for power. For one to understand himself, He must lose himself to the will. The absolute madness - it inspires a great fear. "Will I perish" you will think, "Do I care" it will reply. The line of you and the divine, It dissipates more and more. The great struggle is to hold on. Forever more, to remember "I am me"
‚ÄúRead, learn to be awake.‚Äù

Godless being War to those who are Godless, The sickened beings who secularized the foreign priesthood. War to those who are Godless, They are the enemy of all folks. They have no souls! They are malicious machines! Pity for the ignorant, influenced by the Godless, Bound as slaves throughout their lives. Pity for the Godless, harboring disdain for the heathen. Aligned with entropy! Devoted to never ending pleasure! The Godless have no deity, they have no goal. All they seek is the funeral of the truth. A blight in a darkened age, They no longer use the church for their plague. We must destroy the Godless, They have no purpose. We must destroy the Godless, They drag the weak down with them. They hate the conquest of self, They believe in no Will but their own. War unto those Godless entities, Seen as adversaries hindering the world's rebirth. Destruction against those responsible for birthing the Godless, Those who embody a metaphysics of 'man,' antagonistic to nature.
Ezra Pound : Canto 81, "What thou lovest well remains..."

To every sailor the gods have given a comrade. While one sleeps, the other keeps watch on the bridge. When one doubts, the other gives him his faith. When one falls, the other discovers the oasis if ice for both of them. When my comrade loses faith, I laugh confidently. When my comrade sleeps, I keep watch for him. When my comrade falls, I fight on for the both of us. Because to every sailor the gods have given a comrade. Hey! If you lose heart, I'll laugh joyfully. And if you sleep, I'll keep watch for you. And if you fall, I'll fight on for the both of us. Because to every warrior the gods have given a comrade. Hey! If you fall I'll discover the oasis of ice for both of us. Hey! Song of the comrade, Herybert Menzel

Who am I? What do I do? I have no conquest, except myself. I own no land but my body. I command no legion but my soul; so who am I? Am I a fighter for a new faith? Do I struggle for my race? I see the rot, all so clear. Am I just a mad-man, trying to become clear. A sacred clown, is that I? Will my life, fly on by. Is this my final turn of the wheel, Or is this when I finally am real. I seek beauty for my folk, All they can do is baulk. This grand ideal for the land, What am I? If not it's hand. I accept the insanity of this world, A return to the primordial twirl. I love you, I'll let my love unfurl. An endless dance, thine eyes are pearls.

Until we meet again Until we meet again. On those fields where white roses turn red. Shall we learn again to love and begin again to hate. And when time again stops, when the world again ends. Will it be a noose? Or a bullet instead? Oh how we will laugh when we meet again. I now know theres a devil, he smiles above our heads. There will be time to live, after were dead. So pour yourself a drink, even in jest. Long live we shout, for our god is dead. But we still laugh. For he will reign again. Until then, we wait. For we will meet again. On these fields where white roses shall turn red.

We knew him well,as few men knew His nobility of purpose and his fiery determination To set aright a world of rapidly diminishing values; These tasks to him mattered, Not the Bourgeois struggle for comfort and convenience, Nor the magnet of conformity to the petty edicts Of a suicide-bent Society. When the history is written, There will be chroniclers who will remember The contributions of Francis Yockey- Of Ulick Varange and Imperium. The European Liberation Front will remember, An embattled continent will remember, And honor his sacrifice. H.K.T. 1960

In the beginning, we were few. Our guiding light, ablaze, anew. In our victories, our overcoming of strife. We forgot what kept us right. Our grand enemy, a massive eagle. Where we stood, we saw no equal. A decadent state, our foe's fate. Little did we know, we'd share its weight. Our new world, reclaimed from the beasts. Built freely, liberated from the east. Hands were hardened, but our hearts were hollow. Didn't see the choices that would follow. Conquering ancestors knew the pain, Knowledge of rot in our domain. The city conquered, eternal and bright. Yet, it was blight that took it out of sight. The marble still stands, the people still sleep, But the soul is gone, lessons never to be forgot.

Through my toils, my Brothers recoil. The fear of rebirth, duty's dearth. I'll do anything to find you. My other half, the destruction of me. The seeker, crusader, mourner. Daemon to the age. Demystified, de-glorified, Godless. The serf and the merchant, fearing the festival of madness. Order born of the maw of Ginnungagap. An upward flow, escaping the jaw of fenrir. We sense the wolf, we fear it's coming. Apotheosis is our only escape, This never ending embrace. Only time will unveil, If we will transcend this abyssal hell.

Thralls My ancient lives, I cannot thrive. In this place, I cannot stay. In my pain, I go astray. I fight again, through new eyes. The place I stay, in the Fray. The ages come, the ages gone. Failing, falling, to the empty light. This distant sea, this corrupted land. Slaves of vice, whisper demons cry's. Working for the vice they can afford. Loss of dignity, loss of drive. The ashes fall, reminders of the tower. The weeping civilization, seeing her children. Glowing great light, lost to time. I accept you, I will you. Fight against the downward pull. You hear voices, scratching, pulling at your mind. You think therefore you are; they don't therefore they're not.
Inferiors revolt in order that they may be equal, and equals that they may be superior. Such is the state of mind which creates revolutions. Aristotle

Bury me under the autumn leaves. Where it still lingers, the kiss once so sweet. Remember for me, all that used to be. Her smile reflects a faint longing to die. Were back here again. When will we see? But even the moonlight just retraces the sun. And even my eyes just reflect yours. Bittersweet it is, a flickering flame. Carrying memories, ships crossing the horizon. A faint sense of peace, devoured by the primordial sea. Lost in the currents of her hair. When time comes to a stop. And the candles burn out. Among the autumn leaves. Will you wait for me?

Henotheist That ancient hero, Fought the traitor and invader. From east to west, north to South. The restorer of the world, unification of the imperium. That manifestation of the sun, Glorious conquest. He, like the hero was betrayed. But we remember his sacrifices this day.
Love night walks

Fear I cower at the immense weight. That duty only that the glorious could only carry. Why is it us? The decadent sons? When the God's of our age failed? I pick myself up, When hardship makes me low. I fight for the future, I'm Afraid. It matters not, it's us or naught.

Sacrifice We worship at your altar, Goddess of beauty. Sanctify us! Free us from resentment! Goddess I love, You've given me strength! What could I provide you? Except my devotion. What have I sacrificed? What have I given for home and hearth? I owe you more than I can say. That peninsula, pointed towards the southern pole. I cry out in faith, I cry out for your strength. To push myself to my limits, For my children, to surpass them. The endless chain towards perfection. This goal is endless, It leads to damnation. I seek divine madness, For you I give my soul. Hail to the sun, The surveyor of my life. You saw my weakness, you saw my strength. If I am lucky you'll see my death. I fail constantly, this over-becoming, I see my downfall, it doesn't matter. The sacrifice of the sacred, The hatred of my love. I give it to you Florida, I give you my all. Please forgive my weakness. I'll bleed it out for you. I seek self perfection, Why do I fail? What are base urges, for the infinite? Is it you? Florida guide me, I call out. On those seas that caress my senses. I am weak to your nature. Make me an avatar of your Will. Guide me! Destroy me! Make me! Oh Floriday!

Prometheus by Fidus "Prometheus hung on the rock, His flesh was torn apart by the iron ring. The eagle from the Hether circles, A piece of sore liver tears. Hellish pain convulses through his body, Prometheus suffers heavenward. His anger is clouded, his scorn flashes: "You crown robber on the Chron!" His scorn is clouded, his cronyism flashes: ‚ÄúI laugh at the Almighty God. Down there in the people's hat, how the holy glow grows, how it surges! How she is already licking up to your chair from the forbidden lake! The flame hungers, blazes, longs, The gold melts, the chair groans. Your chron, you god of torment, is crashing in two - Prometheus humanity, become free!"

Family You are born into the world Crying, screaming into the void. You reach out, but cannot see. Your mother, weeping for thee. Your mother holds you in her arms, Loving you like no one can. She'll protect you, day and night. No matter what, no matter the fight. Your father cares, in another way. He wants to guide, show the way. He shows you hard truths, so in the end you'll make it through. No matter what, he loves you. You are older, you think you're right. You know wrong from right, seeking pleasure, chasing fun. You don't know what you've done. Scared, alone, afraid of the world. You just learned, it's a girl. You're a father now, you don't know what to do. But in those eyes, oh so blue. Your love holds her, the center of the world. You'd do anything, for her. Returning to your parents, older now. You ask, what to do now. Your parents explain, they were afraid. What you must do is not evade. Teacher her right from wrong. Guide her with a song, Work with your love, day and night. So she'll be better, a glorious light. You can do this by tracking everything you normally eat for a week on a calorie tracker. BE HONEST! 2. Take that average daily calorie intake and add 300-500 calories on top of that (eat more). Let‚Äôs say you can only do a one plate squat (135 lbs) x 10 while hitting the correct depth. The solution isn‚Äôt to increase the weight and do 10 reps at half depth. Niceness and meanness cannot enter the equation of a successful rhetorical appeal: Rhetoric exists on the polarity of need, not emotion, which is a reaction to need. So, what does it mean to listen? There are three elements to listening: attention, consideration, and response. See, kindness does not often win attention, and meanness does not win consideration. What does win attention? The quality of being estimable. What wins consideration? Common ground, benevolence, sincerity, and exigency. What generates response? I am pleased to announce that with our creation of an Order of Human Heritage dedicated to preserving the human genome, Temple membership is now open to all people: No longer will one have to have avoided the Covid jabs. By dedicating an Order to the preservation of the human genome, we are able to uphold our moral duty of protecting the constructs of nature, as dictated by natural law morality. And, by opening membership to all people, we are able to focus on our primary mission, which is to restore and guide natural religion and work towards the renouncement and prohibition of revealed religion throughout the world. We are very happy with this change. I, Pontifex Maximus Peteseph Brennan Drakontos, am especially pleased with the change. Throughout the years, I have known logically that preserving the human genome was necessary, yet in my heart, I felt excluding people from the Temple was wrong, as I began this Temple prior to the Covid crisis in order to help serve humanity and empower it against its enemies in the first place. With the realization that our moral duties can be realized by creating an order within the Temple, my mind and heart are finally at peace on this issue. New members of the Temple will be given a list of cults and orders they may join, and those who are eligible for such orders as the Order of Human Heritage will be encouraged to join. Beyond that, the order will not be much of a preoccupation within the Temple, and there will not be an awkward divide between members over one's membership or non-membership in this order. It will remain a rule that one should not undergo any genome-altering procedures, and if one receives such "gene therapy," it would not affect one's membership within the Temple but would simply be seen as a moral fault. Finally, by eliminating vaccination status as a membership criteria, we open our doors to all people and make the restoration of natural religion, our primary mission, the primary object of attention once again. This is absolutely necessary to succeed as a Temple, to succeed in restoring natural religion, and thereby to succeed in our moral goals of rectifying the world of its injustices and genocides. I am hopeful that opening the Temple to all people in this way will help people see us as an attractive and viable avenue of religion, and allow us to become successful in gaining members, raising funds, and building physical sites of worship and their associated facilities throughout the world. I ask Savior Apollon to witness my good faith and sincerity, and to bless the Temple and all its members. Our next catechetical program is yet to be determined but is anticipated to begin around the time of the autumn equinox. I will publicly announce when we are accepting new catechumens. Thank you for your patience and support.

The mind is like a pot on the potter‚Äôs wheel. Knowledge is like a cascade of sand filling the pot; Insight is like clay added to the pot, increasing its dimensions, so knowledge may extend further; Attention is required to find the clay and shape it correctly, is the vehicle of understanding and insight; Willpower procures the clay and moves the potter, is the vehicle for actualization and manifestation; Devotion and provides the purpose of the pot, stirred to creation (action) by desire to realize a higher purpose, and ultimately the purpose is the reason, Goodness realizing Itself, celebration, love, play. Willpower and Attention work in concert: By Willpower is one moved, and by Attention is the Good discovered and Knowledge acquired. From these is Devotion born, and from Devotion is the work conceived and maintained, and Knowledge built, understanding deepened and extended. By constant Will, mindful Attention, sincere Devotion, and profound Knowledge, one‚Äôs craft is perfected, one realizes their fullest portion and expression of divinity. Willpower and Attention, Karma and Raja, Fortitude and Prudence, are the parents of yoga, of virtue. Above all, Willpower is the king of all virtue and understanding. The greatest man is he possessed of the greatest will, and this will is not mere ambition but passion. The native intelligence or capacity determines whether that passion matures into piety or ends in zealotry. But, willpower being greater than other virtues by its determination of one‚Äôs capacity for virtue (one‚Äôs dimensions), the unintelligent zealot, possessing greater willpower, is better than the unintelligent apathetic, and probably causes fewer problems, and graciously the problems he causes are very obvious, ideal for the material realm to identify and correct, which is the whole principle of Physis and the purpose of this realm, driven as it is by the Divine Intelligence. The brute is better and closer to God than the liar, yet, of course, it is better to be intelligent and hence virtuous than to be brutish, but this particular lesson for our ignorant, non-authoritarian society is that the brute is better than the liar, that simplicity and courage are better than cleverness and ‚Äúdiscretion‚Äù, that honesty is better than deceit, that the tyrant is better than the politician.

cleaned_message: There is not just an economics of finance but an economics of time. How much time do we have to spend? Are we making it time-wise? Are we wealthy time-wise? Indeed, money represents time, hours someone had to work. So, truly, money should be based strictly off of time and acquired by time, and economics should measure time rather than money and concern itself further with health and willpower rather than market speculation. Indeed, all of man's creations hinge on willpower, time, and effort, not on money. Money is an incentive, but there are things that cannot be quantified monetarily, and creations that are labors of love, vision, genius, and sacrifice, which no amount of money could conjure forth. A poor man may be rich in opportunity if he is not being robbed of his time, but alas, though we are poor financially, our nation is poorer time-wise: While we prosecute robbers of money, we have utterly turned a blind eye to those who rob us of our time! And the system foisted upon us by hostile foreigners keeps us as busy, distracted, and beleaguered as possible to proletarianize us and keep us from realizing the means of our liberation and exaltation as a people. Thus, did Ezra Pound say that there is no lie more black and fetid than that which says a people cannot fix its problems because there isn't enough money to do so. And thus have I proposed that our currency be based on labor-hours, which would immediately elevate the wealth and status of every working person and deprive the parasitical class from their means of robbery, such as usury. There would be an economic miracle and abundant prosperity to be realized for the people; there would be a cause for celebration and pride in work; and there would be a solution to the looming crisis of those who don't want to work when doing so doesn't make ends meet. There, too, would be a solution to liberate us from mortgages, when a house can be raised in a week (by six workers) and its materials produced and shipped with, say, a month of labor-hours. Thus, a house could be purchased with 2-3 months of labor-hours instead of 20-30 years. Do you see how greedily they are milking the blood out of us, and how much better off we could be? Monkeys work 2 hours a day, and ancients had 185 days off in a year, yet we are slaving away day in and day out, without time for cultural participation or contribution. (Indeed, our culture spews garbage upon us and our children.) And for what? For whom? For a small minority to feel they are gods on earth. Isn't it time to stop these bastards and start organizing according to our own interests? If you're sick of the abuse and want to join an organization with real balls, wisdom, and the ability to save people, then consider joining us. Part of our mission is not just to educate people in the true principles of natural religion (which we hold to with uncompromising integrity), but it is also to organize all pagans and folks to defend and promote our interests by establishing a theocratic empire and network of self-sufficient fellowships, to separate from this doomed society and start working towards our own security, prosperity, and genetically-sound future. (We saved at least 200+ people with our Covid vaccine exemption affidavits, and we let go of a few of the priests we trained who didn't want to exclude people for being anti-vax.) We have chosen a hard road for ourselves, but it is the only road that leads to glory and the Gods, and we have saved more people and made more sacrifices than 99% of the poser influencers online. Indeed, we are one of the only pagan religious organizations I know that actually have their 501c3 status from the IRS, which required a $625 application fee and 100-pages of typed material attached to our application, and going through this hurdle allows our organization to purchase real estate (land and old churches, etc.) to erect new temples and local fellowships.
